# Frontend style guide

When you add or change UI in BookHub (`static/index.html`, `static/bookhub.js`, future CSS):

1. **Read and follow `Readme/style.md`** — design tokens, typography, buttons, panels.
2. **Update `Readme/style.md`** in the same change if you introduce a new reusable pattern (component class, modal variant, semantic color).

## No native browser dialogs

**Never** use `window.alert`, `window.confirm`, or `window.prompt` for user-facing messages.

| Need | Use instead |
|------|-------------|
| Info / success / error message | `showAppNotice({ message, variant, title? })` → `#app-notice-modal` |
| Confirm destructive action | `.modal-overlay` + `.modal-box--danger` (see `#delete-modal`) |
| Confirm with diff / custom body | Dedicated modal (see `#ai-fix-modal`) |

## Modals (strict)

All modal dialogs **must** use the shared pattern:

- Outer: `.modal-overlay` (`role="dialog"`, `aria-modal="true"`, `aria-labelledby`)
- Inner: `.modal-box` (+ optional `--danger`, `--success`, `--profile`)
- Actions: `.modal-actions` with cancel + `.btn-primary` or `.btn-danger`

Do **not** invent separate overlay/modal CSS. Reuse existing modal IDs as reference.

Exception: `#login-overlay` — full-screen auth; keep visually aligned with modal-box (see style.md §4).

## General

- Colors via CSS variables (`--accent-amber`, `--bg-panel`, …), support dark + light themes.
- Fonts: **Inter** (UI), **Playfair Display** (headings).
- Buttons: reuse existing classes before adding new ones.
- Russian UI copy unless the feature is explicitly English-only.
